            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> imo this is expected behavior. `~` can appear in path names. In this example, there could be a folder named `~` inside of the PWD, and incorrectly expanding `~` to the value of $HOME could break things.\n\nIt's common for `~` to be expanded **only if it is first**, and in that case (as yochem says) you can protect against expansion by writing `./~foobar` or whatever.\n\n> This should definitely be documented like the other functions are though.\n\nAgreed. Even worse, because I think that `~` expansion is a terrific quality-of-life addition, all the `vim.fs` functions should do the same thing as far as expansion goes. If the pattern so far is not to expand `~`, then neither should `rm`.\n\ntl;dr - Maybe make this a more general request for (initial only) `~` expansion for all the `vim.fs` functions? Either way, the behavior for all functions should be clearly documented.",
