            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> sending things \"literally\" becomes much more awkward\n\nNot a strong opinion here, but how is `'./' .. path` (or `vim.fs.joinpath('.', path)`) to enforce current dir only much more awkward?\n\n> there is a performance cost.\n\nAgain, not that I have a strong opinion but we have a `expand_home()` helper in the fs module that is simply this:\n\n```lua\n  sep = sep or os_sep\n  if vim.startswith(path, '~') then\n    local home = uv.os_homedir() or '~' --- @type string\n    if home:sub(-1) == sep then\n      home = home:sub(1, -2)\n    end\n    path = home .. path:sub(2) --- @type string\n  end\n  return path\n```\n\nOf course there _is_ a performance cost, but looking at the code it seems negligible.\n\n> If that's too awkward for some reason then let's find out why :)\n\nI've always found the slight differences between `abspath()` and `normalize()` a bit awkward. Also the common case where you actually need both, `vim.fs.abspath(vim.fs.normalize(path))`, is quite verbose. But I'm also not sure if introducing a shorthand `fs.resolve()` or something is the solution for it. I've always liked this helper function:\n\n```lua\nlocal function getfile(path)\n  local resolved = vim.fs.abspath(vim.fs.normalize(path))\n  return vim.uv.fs_stat(resolved) and resolved or nil\nend\n```\n\nBecause I find both the abspath + normalize verbose and `vim.uv.fs_stat()` not a readable alternative to something like `vim.fs.exists()`",
